diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: Kawasaki disease is a condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's more frequent among children. The symptoms can include fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, redness in the whites of the eyes (conjunctivitis), swollen lymph nodes especially in the neck, and red, swollen, or cracked lips.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Also known as 'mono' or the 'kissing disease,' this condition is often caused by the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV). Symptoms include fever, sore throat, swollen lymph nodes, and fatigue, but it can also cause enlarged spleen and swollen liver.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: Scarlet fever is an infection that can develop in people who have strep throat. It's characterized by a bright red rash on the body, fever, and sore throat.

diagnoses.name: Measles
diagnoses.description: A highly contagious virus characterized by fever, cough, conjunctivitis (pink eye), a spreading rash, and Koplik spots inside the mouth. Measles can lead to severe complications, especially in children.

diagnoses.name: Viral Pharyngitis
diagnoses.description: This is an inflammation of the pharynx caused by a virus, leading to a sore throat, fever, and swollen lymph nodes.

diagnoses.name: Streptococcal Pharyngitis
diagnoses.description: Strep throat is a bacterial infection that can make your throat feel sore and scratchy. Strep throat can cause significant pain and fever.

diagnoses.name: Adenovirus Infection
diagnoses.description: Adenoviruses are a group of viruses that can infect the lining of the eyes, airways and lungs, intestines, urinary tract, and nervous system. They can lead to a range of illnesses, including conjunctivitis and pharyngitis.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain types of bacterial infections, often associated with tampon use, but can also occur with skin infections, burns, and after surgery. Symptoms include fever, rash, lowered blood pressure, and in some cases, peeling of the skin.

diagnoses.name: Reactive Arthritis
diagnoses.description: Reactive arthritis, formerly known as Reiter's syndrome, is a form of inflammatory arthritis that develops in response to an infection in another part of the body (cross-reactivity). It can cause inflammation of the joints, eyes, and urethra. Symptoms may include conjunctivitis, urethritis, arthritis, and mucocutaneous lesions.

diagnoses.name: Rubella
diagnoses.description: Also known as German measles, rubella is a viral infection that's now rare due to vaccinations. It causes a red rash, fever, sore throat, and swollen lymph nodes. While generally mild in children, rubella can cause serious birth defects if a pregnant woman becomes infected.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of your body. Symptoms often include rashes, lymphadenopathy, and eye irritation.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth. It may also lead to lymphadenopathy and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Meibomian Gland Dysfunction
diagnoses.description: A condition that affects the meibomian glands in the eyelids, leading to irritated and dry eyes. It may be associated with systemic conditions that also cause lymphadenopathy and rashes.

diagnoses.name: Viral Conjunctivitis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the eye's conjunctiva usually caused by a virus. It can lead to eye irritation and sometimes systemic symptoms like lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. Symptoms include rashes, eye irritation, and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: An infection that can develop in people who have strep throat. It's marked by a bright red rash that covers most of the body, fever, and swollen lymph nodes.

diagnoses.name: Rubella
diagnoses.description: A contagious viral infection best known by its distinctive red rash. It can also cause inflammation in the eyes, swollen glands (lymphadenopathy), and joint pain.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. Symptoms can include rashes, lymphadenopathy, and eye irritation.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus is a virus that attacks the immune system. If not treated, it can lead to the disease AIDS. Alongside many potential symptoms, it can cause rashes, lymphadenopathy, and eye problems.

diagnoses.name: Toxoplasmosis
diagnoses.description: A disease that results from infection with the Toxoplasma gondii parasite. It can cause eye irritation, lymphadenopathy, and in severe cases, issues with vision and body temperature regulation.

diagnoses: Autoimmune Thyroiditis (e.g., Hashimoto's thyroiditis in the context of hyperthyroid phase)

diagnoses.name: Hepatitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the liver, which can be caused by viruses, medications, or alcohol. It can present with abnormal liver enzymes, and sometimes, lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect the skin, joints, kidneys, brain, and other organs. It can present with ulcers, lymphadenopathy, and abnormal liver enzymes.

diagnoses.name: Non-Hodgkin lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that originates in the lymphatic system. It may present with lymphadenopathy, abnormal liver enzymes, and increased appetite due to metabolic changes.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs, particularly the lungs and lymph glands. Symptoms may include lymphadenopathy and abnormal liver enzymes.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. The disease can lead to numerous signs and symptoms that may seem unrelated at first, including mouth and genital ulcers, and can affect the liver.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition that causes swelling in various parts of the body, including the limbs, face, intestinal tract, and airways. It is not directly associated with ulcers, lymphadenopathy, or liver enzyme abnormalities but could coexist in complex cases.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) disease weakens your immune system. It can present with lymphadenopathy, ulcers, and liver enzyme abnormalities due to opportunistic infections or medications.

diagnoses.name: Primary biliary cholangitis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease of the liver that gradually destroys the bile ducts. It may present with abnormal liver enzymes and can potentially cause increased appetite through metabolic disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS) syndrome
diagnoses.description: A severe, drug-induced reaction that affects the skin and other organs, including the liver, leading to abnormal liver enzymes. It can also cause lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's disease
diagnoses.description: A type of inflammatory bowel disease that can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract. Symptoms can include ulcers, and while less common, it can be associated with liver problems and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD)
diagnoses.reasoning: Directly related to anxiety; could potentially indirectly influence other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Dental or Oral Health Issues
diagnoses.reasoning: Direct correlation with oral pain. Could indirectly influence mood and stress, exacerbating anxiety or OCD tendencies.

diagnoses.name: Refractive Errors
diagnoses.reasoning: Directly related to difficulty focusing vision.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause anxiety, and in some cases, OCD-like symptoms. Hypoglycemia can also be a symptom.

diagnoses.name: Anemia

diagnoses.name: Temporal Arteritis

diagnoses.name: Dry Eye Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Directly related to difficulty focusing vision. Could lead to increased stress and anxiety in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Pain Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Though not a direct correlation to all symptoms, chronic pain can lead to anxiety, issues with focus due to pain, and mediating medications can sometimes lead to hypoglycemia.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia
diagnoses.reason: A genetic disorder that leads to vascular malformations which could explain vascular anomalies.

diagnoses.name: Sturge-Weber Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: A condition associated with neurological and skin abnormalities, including vascular anomalies.

diagnoses.name: Klippel-Trenaunay Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: Includes vascular malformations along with limb hypertrophy and varicose veins.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.reason: Could potentially explain a combination of systemic symptoms including vascular anomalies.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Granulomatous Disease
diagnoses.reason: Could account for repeated infections like pneumonia due to defective neutrophils.

diagnoses.name: Osler-Weber-Rendu Disease
diagnoses.reason: Another term for Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia, emphasizing its systemic impact.

diagnoses.name: Temporal Lobe Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A form of epilepsy focusing on the temporal lobe that can affect multiple aspects of sensation, emotion, and neurology.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune condition affecting the central nervous system, leading to varied neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: A tick-borne illness that can cause a wide range of neurologic, cardiac, and dermatologic symptoms if left untreated.

diagnoses.name: Ménière’s Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing vertigo, hearing loss, and tinnitus, which might indirectly affect cognitive and sensory functions.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: An abscess in the brain can cause localized symptoms depending on its location, but can also disrupt broader neurological function.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the brain caused by the immune system mistakenly attacking healthy brain cells, leading to a variety of neurological and psychiatric symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Neurosyphilis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection affecting the brain and nervous system, potentially leading to severe neurological issues if untreated.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) can affect the brain, leading to cognitive dysfunction and other neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A complication of diabetes that affects nerves, leading to sensory anomalies including dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Otitic Barotrauma
diagnoses.description: Injury to the ear caused by pressure changes, commonly affecting divers and aviators, which might compound with external otitis and affect balance and cognitive functions.
An infection of the middle ear characterized by rapid onset of ear pain, which might be accompanied by a fever.
A persistent inflammation of the middle ear, typically of long duration, that may lead to perforation of the eardrum and chronic discharge.
A group of mental health disorders characterized by significant feelings of anxiety and fear, which might contribute to symptoms like insomnia.
A common and serious medical illness that negatively affects how you feel, the way you think, and how you act, often causing insomnia.
A type of cancer of the blood or bone marrow characterized by an abnormal increase of white blood cells (leukocytosis) but can also paradoxically present with leukopenia due to bone marrow failure.
A type of cancer that starts in certain blood-forming cells of the bone marrow. In chronic myeloid leukemia (CML), there is an overproduction of abnormal white blood cells.
A condition resulting from not enough vitamin B12 which can lead to neurological complications and hematological disorders like leukopenia.
A complex condition involving persistent pain that can continue for weeks, months, or even years signaling chronic back pain among other symptoms.
A condition arising from an abnormal immune response to a normal body part, which could cause a fluctuation in leukocyte count, presenting either leukocytosis or leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Myeloproliferative Neoplasms
diagnoses.details: A group of diseases that involve abnormal proliferation of blood cells. Basophilia and thrombocytosis are commonly associated findings.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myelogenous Leukemia (CML)
diagnoses.details: A type of cancer that starts in the blood-forming cells of the bone marrow and invades the blood. Associated with basophilia, thrombocytosis, and may present with mild respiratory symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Primary Myelofibrosis
diagnoses.details: A rare bone marrow cancer that disrupts the body's normal production of blood cells. Can cause dyspnea, thrombocytosis, and basophilia.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.details: A type of blood cancer characterized by the overproduction of red blood cells. It may present with dyspnea and thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Essential Thrombocythemia
diagnoses.details: A rare disorder characterized by the overproduction of platelets by the bone marrow. Can lead to thrombocytosis and may be associated with mild basophilia.

diagnoses.name: Hypogammaglobulinemia
diagnoses.details: A condition characterized by a decrease in immunoglobulin levels. It may present with recurrent infections but also needs consideration in the differential diagnosis due to the decreased immunoglobulins symptom.

diagnoses.name: Common Variable Immunodeficiency (CVID)
diagnoses.details: Immunodeficiency disorder that can lead to decreased immunoglobulin levels. Patients may present with diverse symptoms, including increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoproliferative Disorders
diagnoses.details: Disorders of the lymphocytes (a type of white blood cell), which can present with various hematologic abnormalities, including decreased immunoglobulins, depending on the specific disorder.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.details: Some autoimmune conditions can present with thrombocytosis, basophilia, decreased immunoglobulins, and nonspecific symptoms like dyspnea.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Infections
diagnoses.details: Long-standing infections can sometimes present with dyspnea, abnormalities in immunoglobulin levels, and hematologic abnormalities that might mimic some of the listed symptoms.

diagnoses: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) with normal PFTs

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: HIV/AIDS can lead to a weakened immune system, potentially causing leukopenia (low white blood cell count). Hearing loss, though less common, can occur due to opportunistic infections or medications used in treatment. Lymphadenopathy (swollen lymph nodes) is a common symptom. Neurological effects can cause a variety of psychological symptoms, potentially including obsessive-compulsive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: SLE is an autoimmune disease that can cause widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs. It can lead to leukopenia, lymphadenopathy, and less commonly, hearing loss. Gastrointestinal symptoms such as constipation can occur, and neurological involvement might manifest as psychiatric disorders, including obsessive-compulsive behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Caused by the Borrelia burgdorferi bacterium, Lyme disease can lead to a variety of symptoms depending on the stage of infection. Early-stage symptoms include lymphadenopathy. Later stages can affect the nervous system, potentially causing both psychiatric manifestations and hearing loss. Leukopenia and constipation are less typical but possible.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease affecting the body's moisture-producing glands. While primarily known for causing dry eyes and mouth, it can also lead to hearing loss. Neurological symptoms can include psychiatric disorders. Leukopenia and lymphadenopathy may occur, but constipation and obsessive-compulsive behavior are less directly associated.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can affect various organs, notably the lungs and lymphatic system, leading to lymphadenopathy. Neurosarcoidosis can cause a range of neurological symptoms, potentially including psychiatric disorders. Hearing loss is possible if the cranial nerves are affected. Leukopenia and constipation are not typical symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease of the central nervous system that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including neurological ones that might mimic or cause obsessive-compulsive behaviors. While hearing loss, leukopenia, lymphadenopathy, and constipation are not hallmark symptoms, they can appear as part of the disease's complex symptomatology or as side effects of its treatment.

diagnoses.name: Hodgkin's Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system, causing lymphadenopathy as a primary symptom. While leukopenia can occur, especially as a treatment side effect, hearing loss and obsessive-compulsive behaviors are less common. Gastrointestinal symptoms like constipation can arise from the disease or its treatment.

diagnoses.name: Non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: Similar to Hodgkin's lymphoma, this type of lymphoma affects the lymphatic system, leading to symptoms such as lymphadenopathy and potentially causing leukopenia. Constipation, hearing loss, and obsessive-compulsive behaviors may occur but are not typical.

diagnoses.name: Heavy Metal Poisoning (e.g., Lead or Mercury)
diagnoses.description: Exposure to heavy metals can cause a range of symptoms including hearing loss. Mercury poisoning, for example, can lead to neurological and psychiatric effects, potentially including obsessive-compulsive behaviors. Leukopenia and lymphadenopathy are possible, depending on the metal and exposure level. Gastrointestinal symptoms like constipation can also occur.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders (e.g., Hypothyroidism)
diagnoses.description: Thyroid disorders can cause a broad span of symptoms due to the role of the thyroid in regulating metabolism. Hypothyroidism can lead to constipation due to slowed metabolic processes. While less common, lymphadenopathy and leukopenia can occur, and psychiatric symptoms including obsessive-compulsive behaviors may manifest. Hearing loss is a less typical symptom.
Stress Cardiomyopathy (Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy)
diagnoses.details: Triggered by severe stress or emotional trauma, leading to heart muscle weakness.

diagnoses.description: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes (EDS)
diagnoses.details: A group of disorders affecting connective tissues, explaining symptoms like hypermobility.

diagnoses.description: Generalized Anxiety Disorder
diagnoses.details: Characterized by persistent and excessive worry, could be related to or a cause of some symptoms.

diagnoses.description: Panic Disorder
diagnoses.details: Involves sudden episodes of intense fear or discomfort. Could be related to symptoms like sweating and anxiety.

diagnoses.description: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.details: An overactive thyroid can cause symptoms such as sweating, anxiety, and possibly hypermobility.

diagnoses.description: Urticaria (Hives)
diagnoses.details: Dermatographism is a form of chronic hives produced by stroking or scratching the skin.

diagnoses.description: Autonomic Dysregulation
diagnoses.details: Improper functioning of the autonomic nervous system could explain a combination of symptoms including sweating and possibly even precipitate episodes of takotsubo cardiomyopathy.

diagnoses.description: Pheochromocytoma
diagnoses.details: A rare tumor of adrenal gland tissue. It can cause high blood pressure, sweating, rapid heartbeat, and anxiety.

diagnoses.description: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.details: Characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory and mood issues. It could be associated with hypermobility and anxiety.

diagnoses.description: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome (MCAS)
diagnoses.details: An immunological condition in which mast cells incorrectly release too many chemical mediators, leading to a range of chronic symptoms like dermatographism and potentially influencing autonomic and cardiovascular systems.

diagnoses: Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases

diagnoses.name: Recurrent Pregnancy Loss
diagnoses.description: Recurrent Pregnancy Loss is a condition characterized by two or more failed pregnancies. It can be due to genetic, hormonal, anatomical, or immune system abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: PCOS is a hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age. Women with PCOS may have infrequent or prolonged menstrual periods or excess male hormone (androgen) levels. The ovaries may develop numerous small collections of fluid and fail to regularly release eggs.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.description: Thyroid disorders can impact hormone levels, potentially causing symptoms including menstrual irregularities and miscarriage. Both hyperthyroidism and hypothyroidism can have significant effects on fertility and pregnancy.

diagnoses.name: Vulvovaginal Candidiasis
diagnoses.description: Vulvovaginal candidiasis, commonly known as a yeast infection, is a fungal infection that causes irritation, discharge, and intense itchiness of the vagina and vulva.

diagnoses.name: Bacterial Vaginosis
diagnoses.description: Bacterial vaginosis is a common vaginal infection caused by an imbalance of bacteria within the vagina. It may present with symptoms like discharge, odor, and irritation, but can also increase the risk of miscarriage if untreated.

diagnoses.name: Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: ADHD is a neurodevelopmental disorder affecting both children and adults characterized by difficulties with attention, hyperactivity, and impulsive behavior.

diagnoses.name: Vulvar Vestibulitis Syndrome (VVS)
diagnoses.description: Vulvar Vestibulitis Syndrome, part of vulvodynia, is characterized by pain, burning, and irritation in the vulvar vestibule area. It often makes sexual intercourse, tampon insertion, or even sitting uncomfortable.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: GERD is a digestive disorder that affects the lower esophageal sphincter (LES), the ring of muscle between the esophagus and stomach. Many people suffer from heartburn or acid indigestion caused by GERD, which can lead to dysphagia or difficulty swallowing.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS)
diagnoses.description: APS is an autoimmune disorder that increases the risk of blood clots. It is a significant risk factor for recurrent miscarriages and can also lead to other pregnancy complications like preterm delivery.

diagnoses.name: Uterine Anomalies
diagnoses.description: Structural abnormalities of the uterus can include issues like a septate uterus, fibroids, or polyps, which can significantly impact fertility and increase the risk of miscarriage.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden numbness, confusion, trouble speaking, seeing or walking.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief, temporary disruption of blood supply to the brain. It can cause symptoms similar to a stroke, including dysarthria and numbness, but tends to resolve within minutes to hours without permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis is a disease of the central nervous system that can cause a wide range of symptoms including muscle weakness, difficulty with coordination and balance, problems in speech (dysarthria), and numbness. MS is characterized by episodes of symptoms (relapses) followed by periods of recovery.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Brain tumors can press on nerve cells in the brain, leading to symptoms such as difficulty with speech (dysarthria), seizures, and sensory changes like numbness. The specific symptoms depend on the tumor’s location.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: Also known as Lou Gehrig’s disease, ALS affects nerve cells in the brain and the spinal cord, leading to muscle weakness, a gradual increase in muscle stiffness, and worsening problems with speech, including dysarthria.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Some people with migraines experience auras, which can include visual disturbances (scintillation), speech difficulties, and numbness or tingling in one side of the body before the headache begins.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Specific types of epilepsy can cause speech disturbances and sensory symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Guillain-Barré syndrome is a rare disorder in which the body's immune system attacks the nerves, leading to muscle weakness and numbness. In severe cases, it can also affect the muscles that control breathing and moving.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Lyme disease is caused by the Borrelia burgdorferi bacterium spread by tick bites. Neurological complications can include facial palsy, which can cause difficulty with speech, and neuropathy, resulting in numbness.

diagnoses.name: Primary Progressive Aphasia
diagnoses.description: A rare neurological syndrome that involves gradual impairment of language capability, leading to difficulty speaking, reading, writing, and eventually understanding language. It is considered a form of frontotemporal degeneration.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden numbness, weakness, especially on one side of the body, confusion, trouble speaking, understanding speech, and loss of balance.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraines are a type of headache characterized by intense pain on one side of the head. Migraines with aura include visual disturbances and other neurological symptoms that appear about 10 to 60 minutes before the headache begins.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a ministroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief period of symptoms similar to those in a stroke. A TIA doesn't cause permanent damage. They are caused by a temporary decrease in blood supply to part of the brain, which may last as little as five minutes.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a disease of the central nervous system that can lead to disability. The immune system attacks the protective covering of nerves, causing inflammation and potentially leading to widespread physical and cognitive effects, including numbness, weakness, and difficulties with coordination and speech.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Brain tumors can be either malignant or benign and may produce symptoms by either causing direct pressure on the brain or by inducing inflammation. Symptoms might include changes in vision, vomiting, speech difficulties, and physical weakness.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Specific types of seizures might also cause similar symptoms of numbness or weakness.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Meningitis is an inflammation of the fluid and membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. Symptoms can include headache, fever, vomiting, confusion, and in some cases, symptoms similar to stroke.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Guillain-Barre Syndrome is a rare disorder in which the body's immune system attacks the nerves. Weakness and tingling in the extremities are usually the first symptoms. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing the whole body.

diagnoses.name: Hemorrhagic Stroke
diagnoses.description: This type of stroke occurs when a weakened blood vessel ruptures and bleeds into the surrounding brain. The blood accumulates and compresses the surrounding brain tissue. The symptoms are similar to an ischemic stroke and include sudden weakness, numbness, speech difficulties, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Vertebral Artery Dissection
diagnoses.description: A vertebral artery dissection involves a tear in the vertebral artery, which is located in the neck and supplies blood to the brain. This condition can lead to ischemic stroke symptoms as a result of obstructed blood flow and may manifest symptoms like vertigo, headache, neck pain, weakness, numbness, and possibly speech difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.comments: Combination of photophobia, phonophobia, and scotoma strongly suggests migraine with aura. Aphasia can occur in complicated migraine cases.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.comments: Symptoms like aphasia and weakness, along with visual disturbances, could indicate a transient ischemic attack, although careful differential diagnosis is necessary.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.comments: Aphasia and weakness can be signs of a stroke. Neuroimaging is required to differentiate between stroke and other causes of similar symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.comments: Multiple sclerosis can present with a wide range of neurological symptoms including weakness and visual disturbances like scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.comments: While less directly associated with this exact symptom set, meningitis can occasionally present with photophobia and less commonly with other listed symptoms, urging a careful exclusion diagnosis.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.comments: Depending on its location, a brain tumor could cause a variety of neurological symptoms, including aphasia, weakness, and vision changes.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.comments: Specific types of seizures, including some types of focal seizures, can cause transient aphasia, scotoma, and other sensory disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Cerebral Venous Sinus Thrombosis
diagnoses.comments: This condition can lead to increased intracranial pressure, causing headache, weakness, and possibly visual problems and aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Intracranial Hemorrhage
diagnoses.comments: Hemorrhage inside the brain can produce a variety of symptoms depending on its location, including weakness and speech difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Migraine without Aura
diagnoses.comments: Even without aura, migraines can sometimes present with photophobia, phonophobia, and less frequently, the other symptoms if the migraine is particularly severe or complicated.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that is often accompanied by visual disturbances and other sensory symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain, which can cause pressure symptoms including headache and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms like aphasia and ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease characterized by demyelination of nerve fibers in the brain and spinal cord, potentially leading to symptoms like ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain and spinal cord membranes, typically caused by an infection, presenting with headache, vomiting, and sometimes ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus that develops in the brain due to an infection, presenting symptoms similar to brain tumors.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A neurological disorder marked by sudden recurrent episodes of sensory disturbance, sometimes including symptoms like aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Toxic-Ingestion
diagnoses.description: Ingestion of toxic substances can lead to various neurological symptoms including headache, vomiting, and ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the brain tissue, often caused by viral infections, leading to symptoms such as headache, vomiting, and ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Neuritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the vestibular nerve, which can lead to vertigo, ataxia, and symptoms mimicking migraine such as phonophobia and headache.

A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or weakness, and sensitivity to light and sound.
Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. A TIA usually lasts only a few minutes and doesn't cause permanent damage.

Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. A stroke is a medical emergency.
A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Its many types are classified as either primary tumors, which start within the brain, or secondary tumors, which have spread from somewhere else.
A central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

A potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body.
Occurs when a blood vessel in your brain leaks or ruptures. Brain hemorrhages can result from many conditions that affect your blood vessels.
Happens when blood flow through the artery that supplies oxygen-rich blood to the brain becomes blocked, often by a blood clot.

A rare, progressive cerebrovascular disorder caused by blocked arteries at the base of the brain in an area called the basal ganglia. Moyamoya means 'puff of smoke' in Japanese, describing the appearance of the tangle of tiny vessels formed to compensate for the blockage.

A term for brain dysfunction resulting from various causes. It can lead to temporary or permanent damage and manifests with a wide array of symptoms like altered mental status, lethargy, and seizures.

diagnoses: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (formerly known as Wegener's Granulomatosis)
Hepatitis B or C with cryoglobulinemia

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.reasoning: SLE can present with pleural effusion, skin manifestations (such as rashes), and joint involvement (synovitis). Neurological manifestations can include delirium.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reasoning: RA primarily affects joints causing synovitis but can also have systemic effects including skin rashes and, less commonly, pleural effusions. Neurological involvement can lead to symptoms such as delirium.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis
diagnoses.reasoning: This condition can cause joint inflammation (synovitis) and skin lesions similar to annular polycyclic rash. While pleural effusion and delirium are less typical, systemic inflammation may account for a wide range of symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.reasoning: Characterized by distinctive skin rashes, including annular or polycyclic patterns, and can also involve muscles and joints, leading to synovitis. Systemic features might explain pleural effusion; however, delirium is less commonly associated.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Caused by Borrelia burgdorferi, can cause erythema migrans, which might be mistaken for annular polycyclic rash, along with arthritis (synovitis), and in late stages, neurological manifestations such as delirium. Pleural effusion is less typical.

diagnoses.name: Disseminated Gonococcal Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: This condition can cause synovitis, dermatitis presenting with a variety of skin lesions including annular rashes, and rarely, systemic symptoms might contribute to pleural effusion. Neurological manifestations are rare but possible.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.reasoning: A multisystem inflammatory disease, sarcoidosis can cause lung involvement (pleural effusion), skin lesions similar to annular polycyclic rash, joint inflammation (synovitis), and neurological involvement including delirium.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.reasoning: TB can cause pleural effusion, skin rashes through miliary dissemination or hypersensitivity reactions, joint involvement (synovitis), and in advanced cases, miliary TB can affect the brain causing delirium.

diagnoses.name: Still's Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Adult-onset Still's disease can present with fever, salmon-pink rash that could be interpreted as annular polycyclic in nature, arthritis (synovitis), and pleuritis leading to effusion. Neurological symptoms including delirium are less common but possible.

diagnoses.name: Parvovirus B19 Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: This viral infection can cause joint symptoms (synovitis), rash, and rarely, pleural effusion. Neurological symptoms are not typical but viral infections can sometimes lead to encephalitis or delirium in severe cases.
